{{distinguish|text=the [[Public Security Bureau]] official of the same name}} {{Chinese name|[[Jiang (江) (surname)|Jiang (江)]]}} {{update|date=November 2010}} {{Infobox person | name = Jiang Heping (江和平) | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|1|7}} | birth_place = | residence = [[Beijing]] | nationality = {{flagicon|China}} [[People's Republic of China]] | other_names = | known_for = | education = [[Shanghai International Studies University]]; [[Cardiff University]] | employer = [[China Central Television]] | occupation = Television executive | title = Director, CCTV Sports Centre | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = [[Communist Party of China]] | boards = | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }}
Senior Editor '''Jiang Heping''' ({{zh|s=江和平|p=Jiāng Hépíng}}) is a prominent executive at [[China Central Television]] (CCTV), the state broadcaster of the [[People's Republic of China]]. He is responsible for sport coverage in his roles as Executive Director of the CCTV Sports Programming Centre and Controller of [[CCTV-5]], its national sports channel,<ref>It is common in Chinese state-owned organizations for power to be shared between a nominal head, such as Mr Jiang, and the relevant Party official. However, his official biography states that he is "in charge of work" (主持工作), which may indicate that he is ''[[de facto]]'' as well as ''[[de jure]]'' director.</ref> and will play a key role in the broadcasting of the 2008 [[2008 Summer Olympics|Beijing Olympics]].
==Career== Senior Editor Jiang was born on January 7, 1963, in [[Anhui]] province.<ref name="cctv2">{{Cite web|url=http://gbh.cctv.com/20060815/104920.shtml|script-title=zh:江和平副主任|accessdate=2007-09-12|publisher=CCTV|date=15 August 2006|language=Chinese, English}}</ref> Jiang studied English language and international journalism at [[Shanghai International Studies University]]. He graduated in July 1987.<ref name="cctv1">{{Cite web|url=http://gbh.cctv.com/2007/20070820/116169.shtml|script-title=zh:中央电视台体育频道总监：江和平|accessdate=2007-09-12|publisher=CCTV|date=20 August 2007|language=Chinese, English}}</ref> Jiang is a member of the [[Communist Party of China]].<ref>The previous citation states that he is a CPC member. CCTV permanent staff are almost always Party members, and in 1987 graduates were assigned posts by the State.</ref> He was assigned to work at CCTV's International News Division, rising to become deputy editor and editor from 1990 to 1996. He introduced new programming, including the division's first live news bulletins. In February 1996 he was appointed deputy director of the News Department, and was permitted to take an MA in Journalism at the <!-- Note the following is a historical reference -->[[University of Wales, Cardiff]] from September 1996 to September 1997, funded by the [[Her Majesty's Government|British government]].<ref name="cctv3">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cctv.com/sports/special/C14457/20050819/102420.shtml|script-title=zh:江和平简介 |accessdate=2007-09-12|publisher=CCTV|date=19 August 2005|language=Chinese, English}}</ref> He moved to become deputy director of the Foreign Language News Department in 1998, and was promoted to director in May 2000. In this role, he oversaw the launch of [[CCTV-9]], . In April 2003, he became deputy head of CCTV's Overseas Service and Controller of CCTV-9. He oversaw a relaunch of this channel, the launch of a new French/Spanish channel ([[CCTV News (English)|CCTV-E&F]]) and increased availability of CCTV services in North America (''Great Wall TV'').
In May 2005, he became deputy director and acting director of the CCTV Sports Programming Centre. Six months later his appointment as director was confirmed, and in July 2006 he took over direct responsibility for CCTV-5. During the 2006 [[Association football|football]] [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]], he was involved in the [[Huang Jianxiang#The World Cup Commentary 2006 Incident|Huang Jianxiang]] controversy.<ref name="cd1">{{cite journal | author=Xin Dingding| title=Sports host to tackle rumours| journal=China Daily| date=20 November 2006| url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2006-11/20/content_737087.htm}}</ref> Since then, he has been reshaping the channel in preparation for the Olympics.<ref name="xinhua1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.china.org.cn/english/olympic/194590.htm|title=CCTV's Sports Channel Tunes In to Beijing Olympics|accessdate=2007-09-12|publisher=CCTV|date=30 December 2006}}</ref>
==Publications== *{{cite book |last=Jiang Heping |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |editor=Sucharita S. Eashwar |others= |title=Asia Media Summit 2005: Promoting Peace and Prosperity in a Globalised World |origdate= |origyear= |origmonth= |url=http://download.aibd.org.my/books/AMS_05_Promoting_Peace_and_Prosperity.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2007-09-13 |edition= |series= |date= |year=2005 |month= |publisher=Asia-Pacific Institute for Broadcasting Development |location= |isbn=983-41053-3-9 |oclc= |doi= |id= |pages173-5= |chapter=Window on China and the World: CCTV-9 |chapterurl= |quote= }}
